  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Increasing access for disabled girls and boys to primary education in Sierra Leo</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">After years of brutal civil war, the children of Sierra Leone desperately need a structured education - however as schools are rebuilt and restart, children with disabilities almost always miss out due to discrimination and the lack of will, ability or resources to support them. This is because of the attitude of their families, communities, teachers and the education system which do not always think it worth investing time, money and energy into supporting them. This can also lead to disabled children lacking confidence and belief in their own ability to achieve and do well in school. Schools lack any special help and resources they may need - teachers lack support and specific training, and the government has not fully considered how including children with disabilities into mainstream schools is an essential way forward. The education system focuses largely on the provision of &#x2018;special needs&apos; education to a very small minority which can contribute to stigma and discrimination and fails to support true inclusion of all children with disabilities. In Sierra Leone the government is reviewing its educational policy and, as schools reopen to all children, there is a unique moment where change is really possible. This project aims to understand and address the challenges and opportunities in accessing education in this post-conflict country through supporting children with disabilities into and through school. It will work directly with schools to improve accessibility of the school environment and train teachers in appropriate teaching methodologies to ensure children with disabilities are fully included in school. The project will work with three district level education authorities and up to two teacher training institutes in Sierra Leone to ensure that an inclusive education curriculum is integrated into the pre-service teacher training modules. At the same time, the project will undertake rigorous research on exactly what the barriers are at all levels &#x2013; including in families and communities, and in the schools and the education system. As a result this programme will improve disabled children&apos;s ability to enrol and perform well in school as well as improving teacher&apos;s skills and ability to include disabled children in their teaching. Approximately 17,745 children (both with and without disabilities) will directly benefit from the project as a result of improved teaching methodologies, resources and facilities in their schools, with a further 1,780 teachers directly benefitting from teacher training courses. In addition, the programme will help to shape government policy on the inclusion of disabled children in basic education and in doing so, create practical ways to enable much larger numbers of children with disabilities to go to school.</narrative>
  </description>
